<head>CANDLE</head>
    <list type="altnames">
<item>TAPER</item>
<item>VOTIVE CANDLE</item>
<item>ARCHAIC GLIM</item>
    </list>
    <list type="translations">
        <item xml:lang="zh">燭</item>
    </list>
<div type="definition">
<p>SIMPLE SMALL LAMP in the form of a STICK of WAX AND a WICK.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. Zhú 燭 refers to the hand-held torch made ussually of hemp stalks or reed. The word is also used for the torch put in a lamp. Some scholars suggest that the term refers to the candle. WANG 1993: 255; HUANG 1995: 1372; SUN 1991: 351.</p>
<p>2. Là zhú 蠟燭 is the post-Buddhist word for a wax candle. Note that bees were not raised in ancient China, therefore candles were rather valuable artefacts. [WANG 1993: 256]</p>
        </div>
